ğŸ§  OOP Basics
ğŸ”¹ What is OOP?
OOP (Object-Oriented Programming) is a programming style that organizes code using objects, which are real-world entities. Each object contains data (variables) and behavior (methods).
Java is an object-oriented language â€” everything revolves around classes and objects.

ğŸ”§ Think of a car:

Data: color, model, speed

Behavior: start(), accelerate(), brake()

In Java, we model such things using classes and objects.

ğŸ”¹ Key Concepts of OOP
Class â€“ Blueprint or template for creating objects.
â¤ Example: Car, Student, BankAccount

Object â€“ Instance of a class (real thing created from the blueprint).
â¤ Example: Car myCar = new Car();

Encapsulation â€“ Wrapping data and methods together, and hiding internal details.
â¤ Achieved using private variables and public getter/setter methods.

Inheritance â€“ One class can inherit properties and behavior from another class.
â¤ Reuse code. Dog inherits from Animal.

Polymorphism â€“ Same action behaves differently for different objects.
â¤ Example: draw() works differently for Circle and Square.

Abstraction â€“ Hiding complex details and showing only the essential features.
â¤ Done using abstract classes or interfaces.

ğŸ”¹ Why is OOP Important?
âœ… Code Reusability: Use inheritance to avoid repeating code.

âœ… Modularity: Organize code into logical objects/classes.

âœ… Scalability: Easy to maintain and extend.

âœ… Security: Hide internal data using encapsulation.

âœ… Real-world Modeling: Easy to design software around real-world things.

ğŸš€ In short: OOP makes code easier to write, understand, test, and maintain.

ğŸ”¸ What is Constructor Chaining?
Constructor chaining in Java means calling one constructor from another constructor within the same class, using the keyword this().

This helps to avoid repeating code and keeps constructors organized and clean.

ğŸ”¹ Syntax:
java
Copy code
public ClassName() {
    this(parameters); // calls another constructor in the same class
}
ğŸ”‘ this() must be the first statement inside a constructor.

ğŸ”¸ Example: Simple Constructor Chaining
java
Copy code
class Student {
    String name;
    int age;

    // Constructor 1 â€“ No parameters
    Student() {
        this("Unknown", 0); // calling Constructor 2
        System.out.println("Default constructor called");
    }

    // Constructor 2 â€“ With parameters
    Student(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        System.out.println("Parameterized constructor called");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student();      // Calls Constructor 1 â†’ Constructor 2
        Student s2 = new Student("Raj", 21);  // Calls Constructor 2 directly

        s1.display();  // Output: Name: Unknown, Age: 0
        s2.display();  // Output: Name: Raj, Age: 21
    }
}
ğŸ”¸ Output:
pgsql
Copy code
Parameterized constructor called
Default constructor called
Name: Unknown, Age: 0
Parameterized constructor called
Name: Raj, Age: 21
âœ… Why Use Constructor Chaining?
To reuse code across constructors

To initialize common logic in one place

To keep constructors DRY (Donâ€™t Repeat Yourself)

ğŸ”¹ What is Garbage Collection in Java?
In Java, Garbage Collection (GC) is the automatic process of releasing memory used by objects that are no longer needed by the program.

You donâ€™t need to manually delete objects like in C/C++. Javaâ€™s JVM does it for you.

ğŸ”¹ Why is it Needed?
Because Java creates many objects at runtime. Once an object is no longer in use, it still occupies memory.
To avoid memory leaks and improve performance, GC removes these unused (unreachable) objects.

ğŸ”¹ When Does Garbage Collection Happen?
When the object has no reference pointing to it

JVM decides when to run GC â€” itâ€™s automatic, but we can suggest it using:

java
Copy code
System.gc();
âš ï¸ System.gc() is just a request, not a guarantee.

ğŸ”¹ Example (Simple):
java
Copy code
class Test {
    int id;

    Test(int id) {
        this.id = id;
        System.out.println("Object " + id + " created");
    }

    protected void finalize() {
        System.out.println("Object " + id + " is garbage collected");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t1 = new Test(1);
        Test t2 = new Test(2);

        t1 = null;  // No reference to object 1
        t2 = null;  // No reference to object 2

        // Request JVM to run garbage collector
        System.gc();
    }
}
ğŸ”¸ Output (may vary):
vbnet
Copy code
Object 1 created  
Object 2 created  
Object 1 is garbage collected  
Object 2 is garbage collected  
ğŸ”¹ Key Points:
Concept	Description
Automatic	JVM handles it, you donâ€™t need to worry.
finalize() method	Called before an object is destroyed.
System.gc()	Suggests garbage collection.
Memory-efficient	Frees up unused objects automatically.

âœ… In Simple Words:
Garbage Collection is like a cleaning robot in Java.
When you're done using something (object), and no one refers to it,
the robot comes and cleans it up â€” freeing memory for new things.

ğŸŒŸ What is static in Java?
In Java, static means:

Belongs to the class, not to the object.

This means you can use it without creating an object of the class.

ğŸ§± 1. Static Variable (also called class variable)
âœ… What is it?
A static variable is shared by all objects of the class.

ğŸ“¦ Example:
java
Copy code
class Car {
    static int wheels = 4; // shared by all cars
    String color;
}
Even if you create 10 cars, wheels will always be 4 for all of them.

java
Copy code
Car c1 = new Car();
Car c2 = new Car();

System.out.println(Car.wheels); // Output: 4
ğŸ§  2. Static Method
âœ… What is it?
A static method can be called without creating an object.

ğŸ“¦ Example:
java
Copy code
class MathUtils {
    static int square(int n) {
        return n * n;
    }
}
You can call it directly:

java
Copy code
int result = MathUtils.square(5); // Output: 25
âŒ Inside static methods, you canâ€™t use non-static variables or methods directly.
ğŸ”² 3. Static Block
âœ… What is it?
A static block is used to initialize static variables.
It runs only once, when the class is loaded.

ğŸ“¦ Example:
java
Copy code
class App {
    static int version;

    static {
        version = 2;
        System.out.println("Static block runs first");
    }
}
java
Copy code
// When this class is first used, static block runs
System.out.println(App.version); // Output: Static block runs first \n 2
ğŸ”¹ Summary Table:
Static Type	What It Does	Can You Access Without Object?
Static Variable	Shared by all objects	âœ… Yes
Static Method	Can be called directly using class name	âœ… Yes
Static Block	Used to initialize static things at load	âœ… Runs automatically

ğŸ” Example with All:
java
Copy code
class Student {
    static String schoolName;

    static {
        schoolName = "ABC School";
        System.out.println("Static block executed");
    }

    String name;
    
    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    static void showSchool() {
        System.out.println("School: " + schoolName);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student.showSchool();  // Static method
        Student s = new Student("John");
        System.out.println(s.name);         // Instance variable
    }
}

ğŸ”¹ Why new is Not Used with Primitive Types
âœ… Reason:
In Java, primitive types like int, char, boolean, float, etc., are not objects. They are basic data types and are stored directly in the memory stack.

The new keyword is used to create objects, which are stored in the heap memory. Since primitives are not objects, using new is unnecessary.

ğŸ“Œ Example:
java
Copy code
int a = 10;  // correct, simple, stack memory

// Integer a = new Integer(10); // only needed if you want object form
ğŸ”¹ How new Keyword Allocates Memory
âœ… Explanation:
The new keyword:

Allocates heap memory for a new object.

Returns a reference (address) to that memory.

Calls the constructor of the class to initialize the object.

ğŸ“Œ Example:
java
Copy code
class Car {
    Car() {
        System.out.println("Car is created!");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car myCar = new Car();  // memory allocated + constructor called
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ Wrapper Classes
âœ… What are they?
Wrapper classes are used to wrap primitive types into objects.

Primitive	Wrapper Class
int	Integer
double	Double
boolean	Boolean
char	Character

âœ… Why useful?
Needed for collections like ArrayList, which only work with objects.

Help with object features, like using .toString() or .equals().

ğŸ“Œ Example:
java
Copy code
int x = 10;
Integer y = Integer.valueOf(x);  // wrapping
int z = y.intValue();            // unwrapping

// Autoboxing and unboxing (automatic in Java)
Integer a = 5;  // primitive int 5 â†’ Integer object
int b = a;      // Integer â†’ int
ğŸ”¹ final Keyword Usage
âœ… Meaning:
The final keyword is used to make something unchangeable.

âœ… Uses:
Final Variable â€“ Cannot be changed after assignment.

Final Method â€“ Cannot be overridden in subclass.

Final Class â€“ Cannot be inherited.

ğŸ“Œ Example:
java
Copy code
final int MAX = 100;
// MAX = 200;  // âŒ Error: cannot assign a value to final variable

final class Animal {
    // class cannot be extended
}

// Final method
class A {
    final void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    // void show() {} âŒ Cannot override final method
}

ğŸ§± What Are Wrapper Classes?
In Java, Wrapper Classes are object versions of primitive data types.

Primitive Type	Wrapper Class
byte	Byte
short	Short
int	Integer
long	Long
float	Float
double	Double
char	Character
boolean	Boolean

ğŸ¤” Why Do We Need Wrapper Classes?
Primitive types (like int, char, etc.) are not objects. But many features in Java (especially Collections like ArrayList, HashMap, etc.) require objects, not primitives.

Wrapper classes convert primitives into objects, so you can:

Store them in collections.

Use object methods (like .toString(), .compareTo(), etc.).

Handle them in generic code and frameworks that work with objects only.

ğŸ§ª Example: Using Wrapper Class
java
Copy code
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num = 10;                  // primitive
        Integer obj = Integer.valueOf(num); // manually wrapping
        int again = obj.intValue();         // unwrapping

        System.out.println("Wrapped: " + obj);
        System.out.println("Unwrapped: " + again);
    }
}
âš¡ Autoboxing and Unboxing
Java does automatic conversion between primitives and wrappers.

ğŸ” Autoboxing â€“ Primitive â†’ Wrapper
java
Copy code
int x = 20;
Integer y = x;  // autoboxing
ğŸ” Unboxing â€“ Wrapper â†’ Primitive
java
Copy code
Integer a = 50;
int b = a;  // unboxing
ğŸ§  Useful Methods in Wrapper Classes
java
Copy code
int x = Integer.parseInt("123");      // convert string to int
String s = Integer.toString(100);     // convert int to string
boolean b = Boolean.parseBoolean("true"); // convert string to boolean
ğŸ§­ When to Use Wrapper Classes?
When working with Collections:

java
Copy code
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(10);  // Autoboxing happens here
When you need null values:

java
Copy code
Integer count = null;  // valid
int count = null;      // âŒ invalid for primitive
âœ… Summary
Feature	Primitive	Wrapper
Memory efficient	âœ… Yes	âŒ Slightly heavier
Can be null	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Used in Collections	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Has object methods	âŒ No	âœ… Yes

